{"author":{"id":"75732e82453cc4795a3b5d7bef7a9ce916b428e5bbe06161843f7392657be5c1"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1445076330,"nonce":"ykppWa4cPQ3fZvlp/9GLPzY7Czs=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDE0ODkwMTU1MQ==","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/332#issuecomment-148901551"},"message":"Hi Bjoern,\n\nI know we had this discussion once before. My major objection is that by removing the header column we are modifing files in a way that they become different than the original output, only to make it 'fit' within galaxy. The major cause of this is of course that there is (or I am not aware of) no unified standard to present this type of data, in contrast to e.g. alignments (BAM,CRAM) or mutations (VCF). Modifying the featureCounts tabular files would not be an issue if galaxy was a completely encapsulated system (in terms of in- and output of files). But I think that where files go in and out galaxy this introduces problems. If a user runs featureCounts outside of galaxy (yes, these people exist!), uploads the data into galaxy and want to analyse the results in DESeq, they must modify the file (remove the header) for compatibility. This is user unfriendly and we should have the knowledge to overcome this. Similarly, when columns are being removed by the galaxy wrapper and a user downloads the file, it has no columns. I can imagine it is frustrating to download files and modifying them by hand again.\n\n\u003e In general I'm not a fan of providing column names inside of the file. These are metadata and it should be treated as metadata, imho!\n\nYou are right that it is just metadata, but if you reason that way we should strip bam and sam headers too. But here we neglect that the principal of galaxy is that it is a file based and organizing system and therefore you don't want files to be any different than if you would run the same tool outside of galaxy. The metadata can still be interpreted in the back-end and I would be fan of this too, but I don't see this as a reason to strip it from the files. I know header colums are just a small thing but I think it comes with larger implications and I see this as fitting featureCounts into galaxy instead of fitting galaxy around featureCounts. I would rather change Tabular.py or create/find and convert to a uniform file format than to post-modify the featureCounts output.\n\nSorry for the resistace..","files":null}]}